# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: black-veganism
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:black-veganism/2020-democratic-party-presidential-debates-p01] Debates took place among candidates in the campaign for the Democratic Party's nomination for the president of the United States in the 2020 presidential election.
[src:black-veganism/2020-democratic-party-presidential-debates-p01] There were a total of 29 major Democratic candidates.
[src:black-veganism/2020-democratic-party-presidential-debates-p01] Of these, 23 candidates participated in at least one debate.
[src:black-veganism/2020-democratic-party-presidential-debates-p01] Only Joe Biden and Bernie Sanders participated in all the debates; Pete Buttigieg, Amy Klobuchar, and Elizabeth Warren participated in all but the final debate.
[src:black-veganism/2020-democratic-party-presidential-debates-p01] Sites of the eleven Democratic presidential debates.
[src:black-veganism/2020-democratic-party-presidential-debates-p01] In December 2018, the Democratic National Committee (DNC) announced the schedule for 12 official DNC-sanctioned debates, set to begin in June 2019, with six debates in 2019 and the remaining six during the first four months of 2020.
[src:black-veganism/2020-democratic-party-presidential-debates-p01] Candidates were allowed to participate in forums featuring multiple other candidates as long as only one candidate appeared on stage at a time.
[src:black-veganism/2020-democratic-party-presidential-debates-p01] Any presidential candidates who participated in unsanctioned debates with each other would have lost their invitations to the next DNC-sanctioned debate.
[src:black-veganism/2020-democratic-party-presidential-debates-p01] No unsanctioned debates took place during the 2019–2020 debate season.
[src:black-veganism/2020-democratic-party-presidential-debates-p01] The DNC also announced that it would not partner with Fox News as a media sponsor for any debates.
[src:black-veganism/2020-democratic-party-presidential-debates-p01] Fox News last held a Democratic debate in 2003.
[src:black-veganism/2020-democratic-party-presidential-debates-p01] All media sponsors selected to host a debate were as a new rule required to appoint at least one female moderator for each debate, to ensure there would not be a gender-skewed treatment of the candidates and debate topics.
[src:black-veganism/2020-democratic-party-presidential-debates-p01] To qualify for the first debates, entrants had to, at a minimum, achieve one of the two criteria listed.
[src:black-veganism/2020-democratic-party-presidential-debates-p01] If this had resulted in more than 20 qualified candidates, the two criteria would have been evaluated in combination per an outlined set of tiebreaking rules, but since 20 candidates qualified, no tiebreaker was necessary.
[src:black-veganism/2020-democratic-party-presidential-debates-p01] The deadline for candidates to meet either of the below criteria was June 12.
[src:black-veganism/2020-democratic-party-presidential-debates-p01] The **Democratic Party's first presidential debates** ahead of the 2020 U.S. presidential election were held in two groups on June 26 and 27, 2019, in Miami, Florida.
[src:black-veganism/2020-democratic-party-presidential-debates-p01] Eastern Standard Time, they aired on NBC and were broadcast on radio by Westwood One.
[src:black-veganism/2020-democratic-party-presidential-debates-p01] Savannah Guthrie was the lead moderator of the debates, joined by Lester Holt, Chuck Todd, Rachel Maddow, and José Díaz-Balart.
[src:black-veganism/2020-democratic-party-presidential-debates-p01] The DNC drew lots among the 20 qualified candidates for the first debate to determine whether they should debate on the first night (June 26) or second night (June 27) at the NBC News headquarters (30 Rockefeller Plaza) in New York City on June 14.
[src:black-veganism/2020-democratic-party-presidential-debates-p01] The qualified candidates or their representatives were present and involved at the drawing event, which was not televised.
[src:black-veganism/2020-democratic-party-presidential-debates-p01] The debates took place at the Arsht Center in Miami, Florida.
[src:black-veganism/2020-democratic-party-presidential-debates-p01] The first night of the debate was marked by a noted dust-up between O'Rourke and Castro on the subject of immigration, which Castro was widely perceived to have won, while Warren met expectations as a top-tier candidate.
[src:black-veganism/2020-democratic-party-presidential-debates-p01] In addition, Booker and Klobuchar each had their moment in the spotlight, Klobuchar in particular being noted for her one-liners, one of which was about acknowledging that, for the first time in U.S. history, there were at least three women on stage at a presidential debate.
[src:black-veganism/2020-democratic-party-presidential-debates-p01] Gabbard took on Ryan over continuing the US presence in Afghanistan.
[src:black-veganism/2020-democratic-party-presidential-debates-p01] Booker, Castro, and O'Rourke all spoke Spanish at different times during the debate, which received mixed reception and was met with jokes from second-night competitors Williamson and Yang on Twitter.
[src:black-veganism/2020-democratic-party-presidential-debates-p01] On night two, Harris and Biden clashed over Biden's past comments about working with segregationist senators and his stance on desegregation busing.
[src:black-veganism/2020-democratic-party-presidential-debates-p01] The second night was also notable for the performance of Williamson, who received significant attention for comments she made during the debate perceived as strange, including a reference to the Prime Minister of New Zealand Jacinda Ardern.
[src:black-veganism/2020-democratic-party-presidential-debates-p01] Before these debates, no major party had ever seen more than one female candidate on a presidential debate stage.
[src:black-veganism/2020-democratic-party-presidential-debates-p01] The criteria for qualifying for the second debates were the same as for the first debates.
[src:black-veganism/2020-democratic-party-presidential-debates-p01] To qualify for the second debates, debate entrants had to, at minimum, comply with one of the two below listed criteria.
[src:black-veganism/2020-democratic-party-presidential-debates-p01] Mike Gravel was not invited to the debates since he only met the donor threshold, which was given a lesser weight than the polling threshold.
[src:black-veganism/2020-democratic-party-presidential-debates-p01] The deadline for candidates to meet either of the below criteria was July 16.
[src:black-veganism/2020-democratic-party-presidential-debates-p01] The **Democratic Party's second presidential debates** ahead of the 2020 U.S. presidential election were held on July 30 and 31, 2019, in Detroit, Michigan.
[src:black-veganism/2020-democratic-party-presidential-debates-p01] Eastern Standard Time, they aired on CNN and were broadcast on radio by Westwood One.
[src:black-veganism/2020-democratic-party-presidential-debates-p01] Jake Tapper was the lead moderator of the debates, joined by Dana Bash and Don Lemon.
[src:black-veganism/2020-democratic-party-presidential-debates-p01] The drawing of lots among the 20 invited candidates to determine when they will debate was televised in prime time on July 18.
[src:black-veganism/2020-democratic-party-presidential-debates-p01] There were three tiers of candidates that were split between two nights, as opposed to the two tiers used in the first debates.
[src:black-veganism/2020-democratic-party-presidential-debates-p01] In total, 21 candidates qualified for the second debate.
[src:black-veganism/2020-democratic-party-presidential-debates-p01] Gravel, the one candidate to qualify by the donor criterion only, was not invited because of the 20-candidate limit and the polling criterion's precedence over the donor criterion as mandated by the DNC.
[src:black-veganism/2020-democratic-party-presidential-debates-p01] The set of participants for the second debate was identical to the first debates with one exception: Bullock replaced Swalwell, who suspended his campaign between the first and second debates.
[src:black-veganism/2020-democratic-party-presidential-debates-p01] The debate on July 30 featured Bullock, Buttigieg, Delaney, Hickenlooper, Klobuchar, O'Rourke, Ryan, Sanders, Warren and Williamson, while the debate on July 31 featured Bennet, Biden, Booker, Castro, de Blasio, Gabbard, Gillibrand, Harris, Inslee and Yang.
[src:black-veganism/2020-democratic-party-presidential-debates-p01] Both debates took place at the Fox Theatre in Detroit, Michigan.
[src:black-veganism/2020-democratic-party-presidential-debates-p01] The overarching theme on the first night was a clash between moderates and progressives on a variety of issues, ranging from Medicare for All to electability.
[src:black-veganism/2020-democratic-party-presidential-debates-p01] CNN received criticism for allegedly inciting conflicts between candidates and making questions from Republican talking points, as well as enforcing the time limits too strictly.
[src:black-veganism/2020-democratic-party-presidential-debates-p01] The second night saw significant discussion centered on candidates' differing health care plans.
[src:black-veganism/2020-democratic-party-presidential-debates-p01] Additionally, Gabbard went on the offensive against Harris.
[src:black-veganism/2020-democratic-party-presidential-debates-p01] Each of the first two debates took place during two consecutive nights, with a maximum of 10 candidates per night.
[src:black-veganism/2020-democratic-party-presidential-debates-p01] The DNC, at a public event before each debate, drew lots among the qualified candidates to determine whether they shall debate on the first or second night.
[src:black-veganism/2020-democratic-party-presidential-debates-p01] This drawing procedure was designed to avoid the appearance of a "kiddie table" debate where the lowest polling candidates were grouped together with no leading candidates, which happened during the 2016 Republican Party presidential debates.
[src:black-veganism/2020-democratic-party-presidential-debates-p01] The third debate took place at the Health and Physical Education Arena on the campus of Texas Southern University in Houston, Texas.
[src:black-veganism/2020-democratic-party-presidential-debates-p01] For participation in the third debate, candidates were required to meet both polling and fundraising criteria by August 28 (in comparison to the first and second debates, where only one criterion was necessary).
[src:black-veganism/2020-democratic-party-presidential-debates-p01] Qualifying polls had to be released between June 28 and August 28.
[src:black-veganism/2020-democratic-party-presidential-debates-p01] Five candidates (Gravel, Hickenlooper, Inslee, Moulton, and Gillibrand) suspended their campaigns between the second and third debates.
[src:black-veganism/2020-democratic-party-presidential-debates-p01] On August 23, the Gabbard campaign criticized the DNC's purported lack of transparency in the process of selecting organizations/institutions to sponsor polls and how better-ranked polls were excluded.
[src:black-veganism/2020-democratic-party-presidential-debates-p01] The campaign also highlighted the stark reduction in poll frequency, especially in early primary states, after the second debate compared to after the first debate and how they believed that that was "particularly harmful" to candidates with lower name recognition.
[src:black-veganism/2020-democratic-party-presidential-debates-p01] The campaigns of Marianne Williamson, Tom Steyer, and Michael Bennet also requested that the DNC increase the number of certified polls by expanding the list of certified poll sponsoring organizations.
[src:black-veganism/2020-democratic-party-presidential-debates-p01] The **Democratic Party's third presidential debate** ahead of the 2020 U.S. presidential election took place on September 12, 2019, in Houston, Texas.
[src:black-veganism/2020-democratic-party-presidential-debates-p01] George Stephanopoulos was the lead moderator of the debate, joined by David Muir, Linsey Davis, and Jorge Ramos.
[src:black-veganism/2020-democratic-party-presidential-debates-p01] The candidates who qualified for the third debate were Biden, Booker, Buttigieg, Castro, Harris, Klobuchar, O'Rourke, Sanders, Warren, and Yang.
[src:black-veganism/2020-democratic-party-presidential-debates-p01] This gave candidates who did not qualify for the September debate more time to qualify for the October debate.
[src:black-veganism/2020-democratic-party-presidential-debates-p01] Biden, Booker, Buttigieg, Castro, Harris, Klobuchar, O'Rourke, Sanders, Warren, and Yang qualified before August 22, while Steyer and Gabbard qualified on September 8 and September 24 respectively.
[src:black-veganism/2020-democratic-party-presidential-debates-p01] The qualification deadline for the fourth debate was October 1, 2019.
[src:black-veganism/2020-democratic-party-presidential-debates-p01] One candidate (de Blasio) suspended his campaign between the third and fourth debates.
[src:black-veganism/2020-democratic-party-presidential-debates-p01] The **Democratic Party's fourth presidential debate** was held on Tuesday October 15, 2019, in Westerville, Ohio, from 8 to 11 p.m.
[src:black-veganism/2020-democratic-party-presidential-debates-p01] On September 27, the DNC announced that the debate would include all 12 candidates on one night, although some had assumed it would take place on two nights since it had more than 10 participants.
[src:black-veganism/2020-democratic-party-presidential-debates-p01] From left to right, the candidates were: Gabbard (who missed the previous debate), Steyer (in his first debate), Booker, Harris, Sanders, Biden and Warren (who shared center stage), Buttigieg, Yang, O'Rourke, Klobuchar, and Castro.
[src:black-veganism/2020-democratic-party-presidential-debates-p01] Podium order for the debate was determined based on an average of the 10 most recently released qualifying polls.
[src:black-veganism/2020-democratic-party-presidential-debates-p01] CNN anchors Erin Burnett and Anderson Cooper and *New York Times* national editor Marc Lacey served as the debate moderators.
[src:black-veganism/2020-democratic-party-presidential-debates-p01] The debate aired exclusively on CNN, CNN International and CNN en Español, and was streamed on CNN.com's homepage and NYTimes.com's homepage.
[src:black-veganism/2020-democratic-party-presidential-debates-p01] The debate also streamed live on the following Facebook Pages: CNN, CNN International, CNN Politics, CNN Replay, AC360 and Erin Burnett OutFront.
[src:black-veganism/2020-democratic-party-presidential-debates-p01] In addition, the debate was available across mobile devices via CNN's and New York Times' apps for iOS and Android, via CNNgo apps for Apple TV, Roku, Amazon Fire, Chromecast and Android TV, SiriusXM Channels 116, 454 and 795, the Westwood One Radio Network and National Public Radio.
[src:black-veganism/2020-democratic-party-presidential-debates-p01] The Ohio debate featured 12 candidates, setting a record for the highest number of candidates in one presidential debate.
[src:black-veganism/2020-democratic-party-presidential-debates-p01] A memo released by the DNC on September 23 indicated that the qualification period for the November debate started on September 13, and ended on November 13.
[src:black-veganism/2020-democratic-party-presidential-debates-p01] To qualify in terms of polling, candidates needed to reach three percent or more in four polls approved by the DNC.
[src:black-veganism/2020-democratic-party-presidential-debates-p01] Alternatively, reaching five percent or more in two DNC-approved polls conducted in Iowa, New Hampshire, Nevada or South Carolina was also accepted as meeting the polling threshold.
[src:black-veganism/2020-democratic-party-presidential-debates-p01] To qualify in terms of donors, candidates needed to receive donations from 165,000 unique donors with 600 unique donors in 20 different states, territories or the District of Columbia.
[src:black-veganism/2020-democratic-party-presidential-debates-p01] Three candidates (Messam, O'Rourke, and Ryan) suspended their campaigns between the fourth and fifth debates.
[src:black-veganism/2020-democratic-party-presidential-debates-p01] The **Democratic Party's fifth presidential debate** was held on November 20, 2019, from 9 to 11:20 p.m.
[src:black-veganism/2020-democratic-party-presidential-debates-p01] ET, at Tyler Perry Studios in Atlanta, Georgia.
[src:black-veganism/2020-democratic-party-presidential-debates-p01] It was moderated by Rachel Maddow, Andrea Mitchell, Kristen Welker and Ashley Parker.
[src:black-veganism/2020-democratic-party-presidential-debates-p01] The candidates who qualified were Biden, Booker, Buttigieg, Gabbard, Harris, Klobuchar, Sanders, Steyer, Warren and Yang.
[src:black-veganism/2020-democratic-party-presidential-debates-p01] A memo released by the DNC on October 25 indicated that the qualification period for the December debate started on October 16, and ended on December 12.
[src:black-veganism/2020-democratic-party-presidential-debates-p01] To qualify in terms of polling, candidates had to reach four percent or more in four polls approved by the DNC.
[src:black-veganism/2020-democratic-party-presidential-debates-p01] Alternatively, reaching six percent or more in two DNC-approved polls conducted in Iowa, New Hampshire, Nevada, or South Carolina was also accepted as meeting the polling threshold.
[src:black-veganism/2020-democratic-party-presidential-debates-p01] To qualify in terms of donors, candidates had to receive donations from 200,000 unique donors with 800 unique donors in 20 different states, territories or the District of Columbia.
[src:black-veganism/2020-democratic-party-presidential-debates-p01] The **Democratic Party's sixth presidential debate** was held on December 19, 2019, at 8 p.m.
[src:black-veganism/2020-democratic-party-presidential-debates-p01] ET at Loyola Marymount University in Los Angeles, California, and was hosted by *PBS NewsHour* and *Politico*.
[src:black-veganism/2020-democratic-party-presidential-debates-p01] It was initially set to be held at the University of California, Los Angeles.
[src:black-veganism/2020-democratic-party-presidential-debates-p01] However, the DNC announced on November 6 that UCLA was no longer hosting the debate due to a labor dispute.
[src:black-veganism/2020-democratic-party-presidential-debates-p01] Three candidates (Sestak, Bullock and Harris) suspended their campaigns between the fifth and sixth Democratic debates; Harris would have qualified for the sixth debate had her campaign continued.
[src:black-veganism/2020-democratic-party-presidential-debates-p01] Gabbard, a few days before failing to qualify for the debate, announced on December 9 that she would not participate regardless of whether she qualifies.
[src:black-veganism/2020-democratic-party-presidential-debates-p01] The debate aired on Politico.com, PBS, and CNN.
[src:black-veganism/2020-democratic-party-presidential-debates-p01] The candidates who qualified were Biden, Buttigieg, Klobuchar, Sanders, Steyer, Warren and Yang.
[src:black-veganism/2020-democratic-party-presidential-debates-p01] The candidates were in agreement about the impeachment of Donald Trump, which had been approved by the House of Representatives the day before.
[src:black-veganism/2020-democratic-party-presidential-debates-p01] Sanders and Klobuchar had a disagreement about the United States–Mexico–Canada Agreement, with the former opposed to and the latter in favor of ratification.
[src:black-veganism/2020-democratic-party-presidential-debates-p01] Yang, the only candidate of color, expressed lament that Kamala Harris and Cory Booker were absent, and declared that his universal-basic-income proposal would diversify the field.
[src:black-veganism/2020-democratic-party-presidential-debates-p01] Sanders, Biden, and Warren parried a question about age.
[src:black-veganism/2020-democratic-party-presidential-debates-p01] Steyer stated that climate change would be his top priority as president, and the issue was discussed at length by all the candidates.
[src:black-veganism/2020-democratic-party-presidential-debates-p01] The Chinese government censored a live feed of the debate after moderator Judy Woodruff asked Pete Buttigieg if the U.S. should boycott the 2022 Winter Olympics in Beijing over China's alleged human rights abuses of Uyghur citizens.
[src:black-veganism/2020-democratic-party-presidential-debates-p02] A memo released by the DNC on December 20 indicated that the qualification period for the January debate started on November 14, 2019, and ended on January 10, 2020.
[src:black-veganism/2020-democratic-party-presidential-debates-p02] A candidate needed to meet both polling and donor criteria.
[src:black-veganism/2020-democratic-party-presidential-debates-p02] Candidates had to reach 5% or more in four polls approved by the DNC, or 7% or more in two DNC-approved polls conducted in Iowa, New Hampshire, Nevada, or South Carolina.
[src:black-veganism/2020-democratic-party-presidential-debates-p02] In addition, candidates must have received donations from 225,000 unique donors, including 1,000 unique donors in 20 different states, territories or the District of Columbia.
[src:black-veganism/2020-democratic-party-presidential-debates-p02] The candidates who qualified were Biden, Buttigieg, Klobuchar, Sanders, Steyer and Warren.
[src:black-veganism/2020-democratic-party-presidential-debates-p02] This debate stage featured all of the candidates from the sixth debate except for Yang.
[src:black-veganism/2020-democratic-party-presidential-debates-p02] Steyer qualified with 2 early-state polls on the penultimate day to qualify, while the other five all qualified much earlier.
[src:black-veganism/2020-democratic-party-presidential-debates-p02] Yang and Booker met the fundraising criterion but failed to meet the polling criteria.
[src:black-veganism/2020-democratic-party-presidential-debates-p02] Bloomberg met polling criteria but not the fundraising criterion, as he was not then asking for donations.
[src:black-veganism/2020-democratic-party-presidential-debates-p02] Three candidates (Castro, Williamson and Booker) suspended their campaigns between the sixth and seventh debates, with Booker dropping out two days after the qualifying candidates were announced.
[src:black-veganism/2020-democratic-party-presidential-debates-p02] The **Democratic Party's seventh presidential debate** was held from 8 to 10:15 p.m.
[src:black-veganism/2020-democratic-party-presidential-debates-p02] CT on Tuesday, January 14, 2020, at Drake University in Des Moines, Iowa.
[src:black-veganism/2020-democratic-party-presidential-debates-p02] It was hosted by CNN and *The Des Moines Register*.
[src:black-veganism/2020-democratic-party-presidential-debates-p02] Several sources noted an exchange between Warren and Sanders.
[src:black-veganism/2020-democratic-party-presidential-debates-p02] They discussed Warren's accusation that Sanders told her privately that women could not successfully win the presidency.
[src:black-veganism/2020-democratic-party-presidential-debates-p02] Sanders flatly denied this accusation and pointed to his deference to Warren before running for president in 2016.
[src:black-veganism/2020-democratic-party-presidential-debates-p02] Warren insisted that Sanders had said women could not win and pointed out that the women on stage had not lost any election, while the men on stage had lost 10 elections combined.
[src:black-veganism/2020-democratic-party-presidential-debates-p02] At the end of the debate when candidates were shaking hands with one another, Warren was seen declining a handshake from Bernie Sanders; the two candidates then appeared to argue with each other.
[src:black-veganism/2020-democratic-party-presidential-debates-p02] It was later revealed that Warren commented to Sanders, "I think you called me a liar on national TV." Sanders replied, "Let's not do it right now.
[src:black-veganism/2020-democratic-party-presidential-debates-p02] You want to have that discussion, we'll have that discussion.
[src:black-veganism/2020-democratic-party-presidential-debates-p02] Candidates had until February 6 to qualify.
[src:black-veganism/2020-democratic-party-presidential-debates-p02] The candidates who qualified included Biden, Buttigieg, Klobuchar, Sanders, Steyer, Warren, and Yang.
[src:black-veganism/2020-democratic-party-presidential-debates-p02] One candidate (Delaney) suspended his campaign between the seventh and eighth debates.
[src:black-veganism/2020-democratic-party-presidential-debates-p02] The **Democratic Party's eighth presidential debate** was held from 8–10:30 p.m.
[src:black-veganism/2020-democratic-party-presidential-debates-p02] ET on Friday, February 7, 2020, at Saint Anselm College in Manchester, New Hampshire.
[src:black-veganism/2020-democratic-party-presidential-debates-p02] It was hosted by ABC's New Hampshire affiliate WMUR-TV and Apple News.
[src:black-veganism/2020-democratic-party-presidential-debates-p02] Emerging as frontrunners after the Iowa caucuses, Buttigieg and Sanders came under attack by other candidates.
[src:black-veganism/2020-democratic-party-presidential-debates-p02] Klobuchar questioned Buttigieg on his lack of political experience, whereas Biden pressed Sanders to clarify how he would fund Medicare For All and brought up his past stances on gun control, citing Sanders's votes against the Brady Bill in the 1990s.
[src:black-veganism/2020-democratic-party-presidential-debates-p02] Moderator Linsey Davis also inquired Buttigieg on the rise in marijuana-related incarcerations of African Americans in South Bend during his tenure as mayor, which he attributed to "systemic racism".
[src:black-veganism/2020-democratic-party-presidential-debates-p02] Candidates also voiced praise for Senator Mitt Romney of Utah, who was the only Republican senator to vote against Donald Trump's acquittal in his Senate impeachment trial two days earlier, and Lt.
[src:black-veganism/2020-democratic-party-presidential-debates-p02] Alexander Vindman, who was fired from the National Security Council by Trump after serving as a key witness on the trial.
[src:black-veganism/2020-democratic-party-presidential-debates-p02] On the topic of campaign finance, Elizabeth Warren stated that political action committees had assisted all of the non-billionaire candidates except for Amy Klobuchar and herself.
[src:black-veganism/2020-democratic-party-presidential-debates-p02] Another prominent issue discussed in the debate was abortion, with several candidates pledging to only support Supreme Court nominees who will uphold abortion rights and pushed for the codification of *Roe v.
[src:black-veganism/2020-democratic-party-presidential-debates-p02] The polling thresholds were drastically increased since the last debate, with candidates now having to reach 10% in DNC-approved national polls or 12% in early state polls conducted in Nevada and South Carolina.
[src:black-veganism/2020-democratic-party-presidential-debates-p02] Candidates who won at least one pledged delegate in the Iowa caucuses or New Hampshire primary were automatically qualified for the debate.
[src:black-veganism/2020-democratic-party-presidential-debates-p02] Candidates had until February 18 to qualify.
[src:black-veganism/2020-democratic-party-presidential-debates-p02] The candidates who qualified included Biden, Bloomberg, Buttigieg, Klobuchar, Sanders, and Warren.
[src:black-veganism/2020-democratic-party-presidential-debates-p02] Three candidates (Yang, Bennet, and Patrick) suspended their campaigns between the eighth and ninth debates.
[src:black-veganism/2020-democratic-party-presidential-debates-p02] The **Democratic Party's ninth presidential debate** was held from 6–8 p.m.
[src:black-veganism/2020-democratic-party-presidential-debates-p02] PST on Wednesday, February 19, 2020, at Paris Las Vegas in Paradise, Nevada.
[src:black-veganism/2020-democratic-party-presidential-debates-p02] It was hosted by NBC News and MSNBC, in partnership with *The Nevada Independent*.
[src:black-veganism/2020-democratic-party-presidential-debates-p02] Bloomberg, who made his debate stage debut after qualifying only a day prior, was widely regarded by multiple news outlets as having performed poorly.
[src:black-veganism/2020-democratic-party-presidential-debates-p02] Bloomberg's political and personal record came under heavy scrutiny by other candidates, including his previous support of stop-and-frisk policies during his tenure as mayor of New York City.
[src:black-veganism/2020-democratic-party-presidential-debates-p02] The controversial program, which disproportionately targeted racial minorities, was referred to by Biden as "abhorrent" and "a violation of every right people have".
[src:black-veganism/2020-democratic-party-presidential-debates-p02] Bloomberg criticized Sanders's advocacy of democratic socialism by comparing it to communism, which Sanders dismissed as a "cheap shot", arguing that his economic policies were closer to Nordic social democracy.
[src:black-veganism/2020-democratic-party-presidential-debates-p02] Buttigieg, meanwhile, branded both Sanders and Bloomberg as polarizing figures who would further divide the party if one of them were to receive the nomination.
[src:black-veganism/2020-democratic-party-presidential-debates-p02] Healthcare was another issue discussed by the candidates, in light of the Culinary Workers Union's recent criticism that Sanders's Medicare for All policy would replace their existing union healthcare in favor of a government plan.
[src:black-veganism/2020-democratic-party-presidential-debates-p02] In response, Sanders defended his plan by saying that it would expand, rather than take away, healthcare benefits for union members.
[src:black-veganism/2020-democratic-party-presidential-debates-p02] Warren attacked Buttigieg and Klobuchar on their more moderate healthcare plans, likening their lack of details to a "PowerPoint" presentation and "Post-it Note" respectively.
[src:black-veganism/2020-democratic-party-presidential-debates-p02] The televised debate drew a combined 19.7 million viewers on NBC and MSNBC, making it the most-watched Democratic primary debate of all time.
[src:black-veganism/2020-democratic-party-presidential-debates-p02] The qualification criteria remained largely unchanged from the last debate, with candidates having to either garner at least 10% support in DNC-approved national polls or 12% in early state polls conducted in the remaining state of South Carolina in order to meet the polling threshold.
[src:black-veganism/2020-democratic-party-presidential-debates-p02] Candidates could also qualify via the delegate threshold by winning at least one pledged delegate in Iowa, New Hampshire or Nevada.
[src:black-veganism/2020-democratic-party-presidential-debates-p02] The qualification deadline for the debate was February 24.
[src:black-veganism/2020-democratic-party-presidential-debates-p02] All candidates still in the race at the time (Biden, Bloomberg, Buttigieg, Klobuchar, Sanders, Steyer and Warren), except for Gabbard, qualified for the debate.
[src:black-veganism/2020-democratic-party-presidential-debates-p02] The **Democratic Party's tenth presidential debate** was held from 8–10 p.m.
[src:black-veganism/2020-democratic-party-presidential-debates-p02] ET on Tuesday, February 25, 2020, at the Gaillard Center in Charleston, South Carolina.
[src:black-veganism/2020-democratic-party-presidential-debates-p02] It was hosted by CBS News and the Congressional Black Caucus Institute in partnership with Twitter, and aired on CBS and BET.
[src:black-veganism/2020-democratic-party-presidential-debates-p02] Following his landslide victory in Nevada the prior week, Sanders was targeted by several other candidates who attempted to dampen his momentum going into the upcoming South Carolina and Super Tuesday primaries.
[src:black-veganism/2020-democratic-party-presidential-debates-p02] Biden hit Sanders on the issue of gun control by drawing a contrast between Sanders's voting record and his own, noting that he was a consistent supporter of more stringent gun regulations throughout his Senate career.
[src:black-veganism/2020-democratic-party-presidential-debates-p02] However, his claim that "150 million people have been killed since 2007" by guns was fact-checked by CNN as being incorrect, with a Biden campaign spokesperson suggesting that he might have intended to say 150,000.
[src:black-veganism/2020-democratic-party-presidential-debates-p02] Sanders expressed regret at his decisions, admitting that he has "cast thousands of votes, including bad votes", and noted that he had a D-minus rating from the NRA Political Victory Fund.
[src:black-veganism/2020-democratic-party-presidential-debates-p02] Foreign policy was extensively discussed by the candidates, which took up about 25 minutes of the debate.
[src:black-veganism/2020-democratic-party-presidential-debates-p02] Sanders and Bloomberg clashed over past comments they have made regarding foreign authoritarian leaders; Bloomberg emphasized recent allegations that Russian President Vladimir Putin was trying to prop up the Sanders campaign.
[src:black-veganism/2020-democratic-party-presidential-debates-p02] This provoked a reaction from Biden, who said that while Obama did acknowledge Cuba's progress in increasing life expectancy during a 2016 town hall, he did not "in any way suggest that there was anything positive about the Cuban government" and proceeded to condemn the dictatorial regime.
[src:black-veganism/2020-democratic-party-presidential-debates-p02] Both Biden and Sanders criticized the moderators on stage for failing to enforce the debate rules.
[src:black-veganism/2020-democratic-party-presidential-debates-p02] The crowd's negative reception of Sanders led to the proliferation of rumors on social media that the debate audience had been "stacked against" him, pointing to the high entry costs which ranged from $1,750 to $3,200 as evidence.
[src:black-veganism/2020-democratic-party-presidential-debates-p02] Tickets were guaranteed to sponsors, and the ticket costs referred to the cost of sponsorship.
[src:black-veganism/2020-democratic-party-presidential-debates-p02] CNN, Univision, and the Congressional Hispanic Caucus hosted the eleventh debate in Washington, D.C., from 8 P.M. to 10 P.M.
[src:black-veganism/2020-democratic-party-presidential-debates-p02] Five candidates (Steyer, Buttigieg, Klobuchar, Bloomberg, and Warren) suspended their campaigns between the tenth and eleventh debates.
[src:black-veganism/2020-democratic-party-presidential-debates-p02] On March 6, the DNC announced that qualification would be based on "earning at least 20 percent of delegates awarded by March 15", as calculated by the Associated Press or CNN.
[src:black-veganism/2020-democratic-party-presidential-debates-p02] The Democratic National Committee announced on March 10 that the debate would no longer allow a live audience, nor would press (beyond CNN and Univision) be allowed to attend, due to fears about the spread of the coronavirus.
[src:black-veganism/2020-democratic-party-presidential-debates-p02] On March 12, the Democratic National Committee announced that the March 15 debate, originally scheduled to take place at the Arizona Federal Theatre in Phoenix, Arizona, would instead be held at CNN's studio in Washington, D.C.
[src:black-veganism/2020-democratic-party-presidential-debates-p02] It also announced that Jorge Ramos was no longer a moderator because he had contact with a person with coronavirus.
[src:black-veganism/2020-democratic-party-presidential-debates-p02] The debate was primarily focused on the COVID-19 pandemic, which was discussed for 17 minutes and 45 seconds, with Biden claiming the Trump administration rejected test kits from the WHO.
[src:black-veganism/2020-democratic-party-presidential-debates-p02] Both candidates also compared the pandemic to that of the Ebola epidemic.
[src:black-veganism/2020-democratic-party-presidential-debates-p02] In an interview with *Politico* regarding the March 15 debate, a DNC official confirmed a twelfth debate was still being planned.
[src:black-veganism/2020-democratic-party-presidential-debates-p02] Two candidates (Gabbard and Sanders) suspended their campaigns between the eleventh and twelfth debates, leaving Biden as the only remaining major candidate.
[src:black-veganism/2020-democratic-party-presidential-debates-p02] Prior to suspending his campaign, Sanders stated that he planned to participate in the debate.
[src:black-veganism/2020-democratic-party-presidential-debates-p02] It is likely that the debate would have been hosted in an East Coast location, such as New York City.
[src:black-veganism/2020-democratic-party-presidential-debates-p02] On April 8, 2020, Sanders dropped out of the Democratic primary, leaving Joe Biden as the presumptive Democratic nominee.
[src:black-veganism/2020-democratic-party-presidential-debates-p02] In early June 2020, Biden passed the threshold of 1,991 delegates to gain the nomination at the 2020 Democratic National Convention.
[src:black-veganism/2020-democratic-party-presidential-debates-p02] On June 29, 2019, however, the DNC referred to a committee a proposal "calling for an official debate on climate change".
[src:black-veganism/2020-democratic-party-presidential-debates-p02] On August 22, the resolutions committee voted to reject the proposal.
[src:black-veganism/2020-democratic-party-presidential-debates-p02] After Steve Bullock received 1% in an open-ended ABC News/*The Washington Post* poll, controversy arose as the DNC's official qualification rules, published on February 14 and updated on May 9, did not state whether open-ended polls would count towards qualification.
[src:black-veganism/2020-democratic-party-presidential-debates-p02] The DNC later stated during rule guidance given on June 10 and 11, that "polls based on open-ended questions will not be considered".
[src:black-veganism/2020-democratic-party-presidential-debates-p02] If Bullock had been deemed a qualifying candidate by the DNC, then 21 total candidates would have qualified by the polling criteria.
[src:black-veganism/2020-democratic-party-presidential-debates-p02] However, the DNC explicitly limited the debate stage to 20 candidates, so that would have triggered tiebreak rules.
[src:black-veganism/2020-democratic-party-presidential-debates-p02] Bullock and Eric Swalwell were tied for the 20th spot with each candidate having 1% polling averages and three qualifying polls with exactly 1% support.
[src:black-veganism/2020-democratic-party-presidential-debates-p02] In that scenario, the DNC would have had to accept inviting 21 candidates, or invent a supplementing final tiebreak rule (for example, drawing lots for the last spot, or deciding the tie by their number of unique donors).
[src:black-veganism/2020-democratic-party-presidential-debates-p02] However, Bullock's certification letter was rejected and he failed to qualify for the first debate, though he qualified for the second debate.
[src:black-veganism/2020-democratic-party-presidential-debates-p02] During the closing statements for the third debate, in which candidates were asked to recall moments of resilience after a professional setback, protesters interrupted Joe Biden for approximately two minutes.
[src:black-veganism/2020-democratic-party-presidential-debates-p02] According to Jess Davidson, they shouted "we are DACA recipients; our lives are at risk!" The Trump campaign accused the protesters of having insensitive timing.
[src:black-veganism/2020-democratic-party-presidential-debates-p02] Immigrant rights protestors interrupted Biden's closing statement.
[src:black-veganism/2020-democratic-party-presidential-debates-p02] Some people in the audience of the tenth debate booed candidates.
[src:black-veganism/2020-democratic-party-presidential-debates-p02] On August 23, Gabbard's campaign protested the failure of the DNC to release "their criteria for selecting the 16 polling organizations they deem 'certified'" for qualifying candidates for the third debate.
[src:black-veganism/2020-democratic-party-presidential-debates-p02] Several other campaigns, including those of Michael Bennet, Tom Steyer, and Marianne Williamson also criticized the unclear criteria, and overall lack, of qualifying polls.
[src:black-veganism/2020-democratic-party-presidential-debates-p02] On September 8, a *The Washington Post*/ABC News poll was released.
[src:black-veganism/2020-democratic-party-presidential-debates-p02] An initial report from ABC claimed that Gabbard had not received the 2% necessary for the poll to count as a qualifying poll, but the Gabbard campaign announced that she had indeed received the 2% necessary for the poll to count as a qualifying poll, citing *The Washington Post* figures directly.
[src:black-veganism/2020-democratic-party-presidential-debates-p02] To further complicate matters, *FiveThirtyEight* claimed that it had received confirmation from the DNC that the poll did not count for Gabbard but the Gabbard campaign countered by stating that no official DNC ruling had been delivered.
[src:black-veganism/2020-democratic-party-presidential-debates-p02] The confusion stemmed from the fact that the poll data was presented with two sets of results: one of all adults, and one of registered voters.
[src:black-veganism/2020-democratic-party-presidential-debates-p02] Gabbard reached 1% among all adults and 2% among registered voters.
[src:black-veganism/2020-democratic-party-presidential-debates-p02] An approved poll conducted on July 1 was conducted similarly, but it is unclear which category was used for the qualification for the debates, as no candidate had 2% in one category and 1% in the other.
[src:black-veganism/2020-democratic-party-presidential-debates-p02] Gabbard later reached 2% in two other qualifying polls, allowing her to qualify for the fourth debate.
[src:black-veganism/2020-democratic-party-presidential-debates-p02] On October 10, Gabbard threatened to boycott the fourth debate, saying that she believed the DNC and the media were rigging the election.
[src:black-veganism/2020-democratic-party-presidential-debates-p02] On October 14, Gabbard announced that she would be attending the debate.
[src:black-veganism/2020-democratic-party-presidential-debates-p02] On December 9, Gabbard announced that she would boycott the sixth debate, and that instead she would be prioritizing campaigning in New Hampshire and South Carolina.
[src:black-veganism/2020-democratic-party-presidential-debates-p02] She failed to qualify for the sixth debate by the deadline, December 12.
[src:black-veganism/2020-democratic-party-presidential-debates-p02] On March 3, as Super Tuesday results were announced, DNC communications director Xochitl Hinojosa tweeted that the qualification threshold would likely increase, giving the reason that almost 2,000 delegates would have been allocated by the time of the debate.
[src:black-veganism/2020-democratic-party-presidential-debates-p02] This tweet was sent after Gabbard apparently received a delegate and would qualify for the March debate, per the previous three debates' threshold of one delegate.
[src:black-veganism/2020-democratic-party-presidential-debates-p02] On March 6, the DNC confirmed that the single qualification for entry to the eleventh debate would be for a candidate to have earned at least 20 percent of awarded delegates by March 15.
[src:black-veganism/2020-democratic-party-presidential-debates-p02] The threshold was impossible for her to meet to qualify for the eleventh debate.
[src:black-veganism/2020-democratic-party-presidential-debates-p02] Yang, along with Marianne Williamson and Eric Swalwell, complained of microphone problems not allowing them to speak unless called upon when other candidates seemed to be able to freely interject at all times.
[src:black-veganism/2020-democratic-party-presidential-debates-p02] NBC responded by stating that none of the candidates' microphones were turned off or muted.
[src:black-veganism/2020-democratic-party-presidential-debates-p02] After Yang had received what he considered to be his fourth qualifying poll, the DNC revealed that qualifying polls conducted by different organizations would not be counted separately if they were sponsored by the same DNC-approved sponsor.
[src:black-veganism/2020-democratic-party-presidential-debates-p02] The ruling was controversially disclosed by the DNC on July 30, less than one day after Yang had obtained 2% in four polls, rather than on July 19 when the second of these polls had been completed.
[src:black-veganism/2020-democratic-party-presidential-debates-p02] In spite of this, Yang qualified for the third debate.
[src:black-veganism/2020-democratic-party-presidential-debates-p02] In the fifth debate, Yang did not receive his first question until 32 minutes into the debate and spoke for considerably less time than all the other participants.
[src:black-veganism/2020-democratic-party-presidential-debates-p02] Yang and his supporters criticized the network for what they saw as an undemocratic process.
[src:black-veganism/2020-democratic-party-presidential-debates-p02] MSNBC asked Yang to join an unspecified program the weekend of November 24, but Yang said he would not appear until the network "apologizes on-air" and "discusses and includes [his] campaign consistent with [his] polling".
[src:black-veganism/2020-democratic-party-presidential-debates-p02] Yang ended his boycott on December 27 by going on the TV show *All in with Chris Hayes*, stating "I decided that I'd prefer to speak to as many Americans as possible – our message is too important" on Twitter.
[src:black-veganism/2020-democratic-party-presidential-debates-p02] Yang requested for the DNC to conduct more early state polls in December due to a lack of early state polling by qualifying pollsters.
[src:black-veganism/2020-democratic-party-presidential-debates-p02] The DNC rejected this idea saying that conducting its own polls would call into question its impartiality.
[src:black-veganism/2020-democratic-party-presidential-debates-p02] The sixth debate was initially set to be held at the University of California, Los Angeles.
[src:black-veganism/2020-democratic-party-presidential-debates-p02] Due to a Sodexo worker strike at the new venue, Loyola Marymount University, Warren announced that she would not attend the debate unless the labor dispute was resolved, followed soon after by Sanders and Yang.
[src:black-veganism/2020-democratic-party-presidential-debates-p02] All of the remaining qualifying candidates (Biden, Buttigieg, Klobuchar, and Steyer) then followed suit over the next several days.
[src:black-veganism/2020-democratic-party-presidential-debates-p02] The dispute was resolved on December 17, allowing the debate to move forward.
[src:black-veganism/2020-democratic-party-presidential-debates-p02] Days before the December 2019 debate, for which Booker did not qualify, he sent a petition to the other candidates' campaigns in which he urged the DNC to change the qualification requirements for the upcoming debates in 2020 so that more non-white candidates could participate.
[src:black-veganism/2020-democratic-party-presidential-debates-p02] All candidates that qualified for the December debate as well as Castro signed the petition.
[src:black-veganism/2020-democratic-party-presidential-debates-p02] The DNC rejected the request to change the qualification criteria.
[src:black-veganism/2020-democratic-party-presidential-debates-p02] The petition cites the New Hampshire Democratic Party central committee which voted to urge the DNC to "lift the barriers" on participation in further debates.
[src:black-veganism/2020-democratic-party-presidential-debates-p02] During the seventh Democratic debate, January 14, hosted by CNN and the *Des Moines Register*, the wording of a series of questions from moderator Abby Phillip directed at senators Sanders and Warren drew criticisms from various other news outlets and from Sanders supporters.
[src:black-veganism/2020-democratic-party-presidential-debates-p02] MSNBC hosts Mika Brzezinski and Donny Deutsch the next day on *Morning Joe* criticized the question, describing it as "bizarre" and "a miss" respectively.
[src:black-veganism/2020-democratic-party-presidential-debates-p02] Senior reporter at *HuffPost* Zach Carter stated that he believes CNN "botched" the debate and Matt Taibbi from *Rolling Stone* described the moderation as "shameful" and "villainous".
[src:black-veganism/2020-democratic-party-presidential-debates-p02] Jeet Heer from *The Nation* commented that CNN was "the biggest loser of the night." *Washington Examiner* senior commentary writer Becket Adams described Phillip's question as "a hatchet job".
[src:black-veganism/2020-democratic-party-presidential-debates-p02] The controversy also led to negative reactions on social media.
[src:black-veganism/2020-democratic-party-presidential-debates-p02] In January, Michael Bloomberg became the only candidate to simultaneously reach the polling threshold and fail to reach the donor threshold since the DNC began requiring both with the third debate.
[src:black-veganism/2020-democratic-party-presidential-debates-p02] On January 31, the DNC announced that it would not impose a donor threshold starting with the ninth debate.
[src:black-veganism/2020-democratic-party-presidential-debates-p02] She argued that the rule change was "not designed to benefit any one candidate" and declared that "every candidate has an equal opportunity to qualify".
[src:black-veganism/2020-democratic-party-presidential-debates-p02] Four candidates opposed the DNC's changing the rules allegedly to make sure Bloomberg qualifies for the debates.
[src:black-veganism/2020-democratic-party-presidential-debates-p02] Weaver stated that the rules changing "in the middle of the game" was wrong and "the definition of a rigged system".
[src:black-veganism/2020-democratic-party-presidential-debates-p02] He also complained that Bloomberg "is trying to buy his way into the Democratic nomination".
[src:black-veganism/2020-democratic-party-presidential-debates-p02] Warren tweeted, referencing Bloomberg's personal wealth, that "[b]illionaires shouldn't be allowed to play by different rules".
[src:black-veganism/2020-democratic-party-presidential-debates-p02] She further objected that the DNC failed to change the debate qualification rules to "ensure diverse candidates could remain on the debate stage".
[src:black-veganism/2020-democratic-party-presidential-debates-p02] Biden responded to a question about the issue by pointing out that Bloomberg is not "even on the ballot in Nevada" (the location of the first debate where Bloomberg qualified).
[src:black-veganism/2020-democratic-party-presidential-debates-p02] On the other hand, two of the candidates welcomed Bloomberg's inclusion.
[src:black-veganism/2020-democratic-party-presidential-debates-p02] Buttigieg told reporters, "It is important that we have that process where folks have to stand with their competitors and explain why each of us is the best." Klobuchar took it a bit further, and stated that he should have to answer questions and not "hide behind the airwaves".
[src:black-veganism/2020-democratic-party-presidential-debates-p02] She claimed that although she could not beat him "on the airwaves", she could beat him in a debate.
[src:black-veganism/2020-democratic-party-presidential-debates-p02] There were accusations online and in the media that Bloomberg had stacked the audience in his favor, though nothing was ever proven.
[src:black-veganism/2020-democratic-party-presidential-debates-p02] The high ticket prices to the event were also heavily condemned.
[src:black-veganism/2020-democratic-party-presidential-debates-p02] A 60-second ad for Bloomberg's campaign played during the first and second commercial breaks, drawing ire, especially online.
[src:black-veganism/2020-democratic-party-presidential-debates-p02] CBS was also widely criticized for doing a poor job of moderating the debate and letting candidates talk over each other, often leading to 10–20 seconds of unintelligible shouting.
[src:black-veganism/2020-democratic-party-presidential-debates-p02] Following Super Tuesday, the DNC and CNN announced that the eleventh debate would occur in a seated format with "a more intimate setting" and a "town hall-style production featuring audience questions," instead of the traditional format of the prior debates led by formal moderator questioning.
[src:black-veganism/2020-democratic-party-presidential-debates-p02] This announcement was opposed by the Sanders campaign as "giving Biden too much of a break" and avoiding an "exchange of ideas", as well as criticized by commentators.
[src:black-veganism/2020-democratic-party-presidential-debates-p02] These concerns became moot after the coronavirus pandemic forced the debate to be changed to the traditional moderator questioning format without any audience.
[src:black-veganism/5-a-day] Eating fruit and vegetables improves health and well being.
[src:black-veganism/5-a-day] Increasing vegetable intake to this desired level has a variety of major and minor health benefits.
[src:black-veganism/5-a-day] Benefits include reduction in the risk of many types of cancer, hypertension, heart disease, stroke, and diabetes.
[src:black-veganism/5-a-day] The National Cancer Institute provided research for the program, while the Produce for Better Health Foundation implemented the program into the food service industry.
[src:black-veganism/5-a-day] In Canada, the Canadian Produce Marketing Association (CPMA), the Heart and Stroke Foundation's Health Check Program, and the Canadian Cancer Society have partnered together to create the **Fruits and Veggies — Mix it up!** campaign, encouraging Canadian families to eat more healthily.
[src:black-veganism/5-a-day] The campaign focuses on easy ways for people to eat healthy wherever and whenever they can.
[src:black-veganism/5-a-day] The French PNNS (*Programme national nutrition santé*, National nutrition health programme) recommends at least five portions of fruit and/or vegetables per day.
[src:black-veganism/5-a-day] The *5 am Tag* (5 a Day) program operates in Germany.
[src:black-veganism/5-a-day] The 5 A Day campaign in Japan is administered by an NPO: 5 A DAY Association-Japan (一般社団法人 ファイブ・ア・デイ協会).
[src:black-veganism/5-a-day] The program recommends five servings a day totaling 350 grams of vegetables and 200 grams of fruit.
[src:black-veganism/5-a-day] 5 A Day is also known as ***5 + A Day*** in New Zealand.
[src:black-veganism/5-a-day] *5 + A Day* was founded in New Zealand in 1994 by non-profit United Fresh New Zealand and became a Charitable Trust in 2007.
[src:black-veganism/5-a-day] The programme was introduced by the UK Department of Health in the winter of 2002–2003, and received some adverse media attention because of the high and rising costs of fresh fruit and vegetables.
[src:black-veganism/5-a-day] After ten years, research suggested that few people were meeting the target.
[src:black-veganism/5-a-day] The campaign has come under criticism from Channel 4 because of government failure to prevent the food industry from claiming that their products constitute part of a five a day despite having added salt, sugar or fat.
[src:black-veganism/5-a-day] In April 2014, a study by University College London concluded that '5 a day' was not enough and that a healthy diet should contain 7 or more portions of fruit and vegetables.
[src:black-veganism/5-a-day] Celebrity chef, Jamie Oliver, recommended between 7-11 portions of fruits and vegetables.
[src:black-veganism/5-a-day] The 5 a Day program in the United States was originally the National Fruit and Vegetable Program but was rebranded Fruits & Veggies – More Matters in March 2007.
[src:black-veganism/a-breeze-harper] Harper attributes her initial interest in practicing veganism to the influence of the work of Dick Gregory in connecting diet to the liberation struggle of marginalized groups, and to Afrocentric, raw foodist Queen Afua.
[src:black-veganism/a-breeze-harper] In 2015, Harper organized a conference, *The Vegan Praxis of Black Lives Matters*, to discuss intersectional issues concerning veganism and the Black Lives Matter movement.
[src:black-veganism/a-breeze-harper] In the same year, Harper joined the advisory board for *Black Vegans Rock*.
[src:black-veganism/a-breeze-harper] Harper was the Humane Party's vice-presidential nominee for the 2016 U.S. presidential election.
[src:black-veganism/a-cow-at-my-table] It covers the conflict between animal rights advocates and the meat industry, and their respective attempts to influence consumers.
[src:black-veganism/a-cow-at-my-table] It was directed, shot, and edited by Jennifer Abbott, who spent five years travelling across Canada, the United States, Australia and New Zealand to interview representatives on all sides.
[src:black-veganism/a-cow-at-my-table] The film intercuts these interviews with images of farm animals and industrial farming operations.
[src:black-veganism/a-cow-at-my-table] It explores what is sometimes popularly called factory farming.
[src:black-veganism/a-cow-at-my-table] The filming of *A Cow at My Table* drew early criticism from the Canadian meat industry, with both the Ontario Chicken Marketing Board and the Dairy Farmers of Ontario publishing articles warning of Abbott's actions.
[src:black-veganism/a-cow-at-my-table] Music for the film was performed by Oh Susanna.
[src:black-veganism/a-fleshless-diet] Buttner obtained his M.D. from Yale Medical School in 1909 and received the Campbell Gold Medal for the highest rank on his examination and the Keese Prize for his thesis.
[src:black-veganism/a-fleshless-diet] In 1916, Buttner was described by the editor of the *Journal of the American Medical Association* as a "recognized representative in the literature of vegetarianism." He argued for vegetarianism from a scientific basis.
[src:black-veganism/a-fleshless-diet] Buttner practiced medicine in New Haven, Connecticut.
[src:black-veganism/a-fleshless-diet] He was a member of the New Haven County Medical Association.
[src:black-veganism/a-fleshless-diet] Buttner is best known for his vegetarian book *A Fleshless Diet*, published in 1910.
[src:black-veganism/a-fleshless-diet] It was widely reviewed in medical journals with a mixed response.
[src:black-veganism/a-fleshless-diet] Buttner argued that comparative anatomy and nutrition demonstrates that man is suited for a fleshless diet and that meat is dangerous and unnecessary.
[src:black-veganism/a-fleshless-diet] His recommended diet consisted of vegetables, eggs and milk.
[src:black-veganism/a-fleshless-diet] Buttner wrote that "It is not illogical for vegetarians to use milk and eggs, as these animal products are distinctly less toxic than meat and also less likely to be disease-laden.
[src:black-veganism/a-fleshless-diet] A review in the *American Physical Education Review*, praised the book for compiling useful dietetic research but commented that it failed to show scientific discretion in the selected material.
[src:black-veganism/a-fleshless-diet] A review in the *Journal of the American Medical Association* recommended the book as a reference work whether or not one accepts Buttner's conclusions.
[src:black-veganism/a-fleshless-diet] A review in *The Medical Standard*, noted that the book was a "piece of special pleading for the propaganda which it is designed to promote […] We may say this, however, for Dr.
[src:black-veganism/a-place-at-the-table] Participant Media is the entertainment company behind the film, and it is distributed by Magnolia Pictures.
[src:black-veganism/a-place-at-the-table] The Participant/Magnolia team is also responsible for the film *Food, Inc.* (2008).
[src:black-veganism/a-place-at-the-table] The film was originally titled *Finding North* but the name was later changed to *A Place at the Table*.
[src:black-veganism/a-place-at-the-table] As of 2012, about 50 million Americans were food insecure.
[src:black-veganism/a-place-at-the-table] This was approximately 1 in 6 of the overall population, with the proportion of children facing food insecurity even higher at about 1 in 4.
[src:black-veganism/a-place-at-the-table] One in every two children receive federal food assistance.
[src:black-veganism/a-place-at-the-table] Other Americans struggling with hunger are also featured, including a cop whose monthly paychecks only leaves him enough money to buy food for two weeks, forcing him to use a food bank.
[src:black-veganism/a-place-at-the-table] There is also a companion book titled *A Place at the Table: The Crisis of 49 Million Hungry Americans and How to Solve It,* edited by Peter Pringle and published by Public Affairs.
[src:black-veganism/a-place-at-the-table] The book features contributions from Jeff Bridges, Ken Cook, Marion Nestle, Bill Shore, Joel Berg, Robert Egger, Janet Poppendieck, David Beckmann, Mariana Chilton, Tom Colicchio, Jennifer Harris, Andy Fisher, Kelly Meyer and directors Kristi Jacobson and Lori Silverbush.
[src:black-veganism/a-place-at-the-table] The film was nominated for Grand Jury Prize at the 2012 Sundance Film Festival.
[src:black-veganism/a-place-at-the-table] At the 2013 IDA Documentary Awards, the film received the Pare Lorentz Award, which recognizes films for model filmmaking while focusing on the use of the natural environment, and justice for all and the illumination of pressing social problems.
[src:black-veganism/a-place-at-the-table] As of October 2015, it has a 90% approval ratings from 61 professional reviews aggregated by Rotten Tomatoes.
[src:black-veganism/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] Salt was active in a number of reform causes in the late 19th century, including prison reform, education, socialism, and animal protection.
[src:black-veganism/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] He later founded the Humanitarian League in 1891.
[src:black-veganism/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] In *A Plea for Vegetarianism and Other Essays*, he argued that a vegetarian diet was humane, economical, and practicable, and challenged common objections to abstention from meat.
[src:black-veganism/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] Across these essays, Salt defends vegetarianism on ethical, social, and economic grounds.
[src:black-veganism/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] He argues against the killing of animals for food, disputes the view that meat is necessary for health, and links diet to wider questions of conduct and social reform.
[src:black-veganism/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] Several essays also attack blood sports and reply to objections made by critics of vegetarianism, including Sir Henry Thompson.
[src:black-veganism/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] Themes developed in *A Plea for Vegetarianism and Other Essays* appeared again in Salt's later writings, including *Animals' Rights: Considered in Relation to Social Progress* (1892).
[src:black-veganism/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] At a social meeting organised by the London Vegetarian Society on 20 November 1931, Gandhi said that Salt's *A Plea for Vegetarianism* had shown him that vegetarianism was "a moral duty" and not only a matter of custom or personal vow.
[src:black-veganism/black-veganism] A 2015 survey found that about 8% of Black Americans are vegetarian or vegan, compared to a rate of 3.4% for all those surveyed.
[src:black-veganism/black-veganism] Veganism as a named movement historically was made up primarily of white people, and the stereotypical vegan is white; Khushbu Shah pointed out in 2018 that not until the bottom of the third page on Shutterstock was a person of color included among the images for the search term "vegan person".
[src:black-veganism/black-veganism] Omowale Adewale, founder of New York City's Black VegFest, argues that there is a history of Black veganism in the US, but said in 2020 that the recent increase in Black veganism is partially because "You love to see yourself represented.
[src:black-veganism/black-veganism] That's one of the main reasons why the Black community has really galvanised around the vegan idea".
[src:black-veganism/black-veganism] It also has roots in the American Civil Rights movement; Dick Gregory, who marched with Martin Luther King, Jr., argued that "Because I'm a civil rights activist, I am also an animal rights activist.
[src:black-veganism/black-veganism] Animals and humans suffer and die alike." According to Amirah Mercer, by the 1980s veganism had "settled firmly into celebrity and activist pockets" among Black people in the US.
[src:black-veganism/black-veganism] The 1990 hip hop song "Beef" by KRS-One, according to Keith Tucker, founder of Hip Hop is Green vegan advocacy group, influenced many in the hip hop community to think about veganism and "meat in the slave diet".
[src:black-veganism/black-veganism] Adams argued, "Now is the time for us to listen to and embrace black veganism." In the late 1990s and early 2000s, Queen Afua played an influential role in promoting Black raw veganism.
[src:black-veganism/black-veganism] She advocated using food as a tool for healing Black women's reproductive and spiritual health.
[src:black-veganism/black-veganism] Aph and Syl Ko are prominent Black philosophers, together they contributed a philosophical framework for Black veganism.
[src:black-veganism/black-veganism] Syl Ko conceptualizes Black veganism as a critique of society's perception of animals.
[src:black-veganism/black-veganism] In 2021,*The Washington Post*, citing a Gallup report, referred to Black people as the fastest-growing demographic of vegans.
[src:black-veganism/black-veganism] In the United States, Black veganism is a social and political philosophy as well as a diet.
[src:black-veganism/black-veganism] It connects the use of non-human animals with other social justice concerns such as racism, and with the lasting effects of slavery, such as the subsistence diets of enslaved people enduring as familial and cultural food traditions.
[src:black-veganism/black-veganism] Dietary changes caused by the Great Migration also meant former farmers, who had previously been able to grow or forage their own vegetables, became reliant on processed foods.
[src:black-veganism/black-veganism] Adams described Black veganism as a "lens of race and animality" through which veganism could be understood as a radical movement for social justice.Additionally, health issues within the black community have been cited as catalysts for people of color to become vegan.
[src:black-veganism/black-veganism] Diet-related conditions include diabetes, heart disease, hypertension, and stroke.
[src:black-veganism/black-veganism] Syl Ko starts from a framework initially discussed by Peter Singer but which does not consider race.
[src:black-veganism/black-veganism] According to Syl Ko, Black veganism is "an animal ethic generated from within an anti-racist commitment." She and her sister proposed developing a "revolutionary" concept of animal ethics that removes non-human animals from the discussion.
[src:black-veganism/black-veganism] Ko told the Brooks Institute that the debate about ethical veganism was whether speciesism was just like racism or sexism; she and her sister had framed it around the idea that speciesism and racism were the same thing.
[src:black-veganism/black-veganism] Syl Ko and Aph Ko conceptualized a theoretical framework for Black veganism, but in praxis there are also Black communities that define Black veganism as cultural-specific practice.
[src:black-veganism/black-veganism] Some Black vegans that consider race in important component to their food practice, who also believe in speciesism, connect the violence of systemic racism and the legacy of slavery to the violence that is currently exerted over Black people today and non-human animals.
[src:black-veganism/black-veganism] According to AshEL Eldridge, an Oakland activist, the movement is about the Black community reclaiming its food sovereignty and "decolonizing" the diet of Black Americans.
[src:black-veganism/black-veganism] According to Shah, the area where most vegans of color feel the greatest rift with mainstream veganism is in mainstream veganism's failure to recognize the intersectionality with other social justice issues such as food access.
[src:black-veganism/black-veganism] PETA columnist Zachary Tolivar noted he had often heard Black veganism called "a revolutionary act" because it often involves rejecting both family tradition and systemic oppression.
[src:black-veganism/black-veganism] Mercer described it as "revoking my own Black card" and said that for US Black people, choosing veganism was an act of protest against disenfranchisement by governmental health care and food policy.
[src:black-veganism/black-veganism] The Institute for Critical Animal Studies in 2021 called Black veganism an "emerging discipline".
[src:black-veganism/black-veganism] Breeze Harper's *Sistah Vegan* and McQuirter's *By Any Greens Necessary* were published.
[src:black-veganism/black-veganism] In the anthology, *Sistah Vegan,* the editor Dr.
[src:black-veganism/black-veganism] Breeze Harper, a prominent critical race feminist scholar, argued that veganism is a tool for combating environmental injustice, health inequities, and internalized colonization.
[src:black-veganism/black-veganism] Prominent African-Americans have publicly discussed their veganism.
[src:black-veganism/black-veganism] In 2011, Oprah Winfrey's staff went vegan for a week and produced a show about the experience.
[src:black-veganism/black-veganism] David Carter made headlines as the "300-pound vegan" after adopting a vegan diet in 2014.
[src:black-veganism/black-veganism] In 2017, Bleacher Report published a story about multiple Black NBA players having adopted a vegan diet.
[src:black-veganism/black-veganism] Beyonce has discussed her experimentation with plant-based eating.
[src:black-veganism/black-veganism] Senator Cory Booker's veganism was discussed during his 2020 presidential campaign.
[src:black-veganism/black-veganism] A *Los Angeles Times* article featured the headline "Cory Booker could be our first vegan president." When asked about it at the third Democratic presidential debate, he discussed the factory farming system.
[src:black-veganism/black-veganism] New York City Mayor Eric Adams is the first vegan leader of that metropolis.
[src:black-veganism/black-veganism] Veganism was particularly embraced by the hip hop community in the late 2010s and early 2020s.
[src:black-veganism/black-veganism] In 2016 "health and wellness", including a plant-based diet, was added as the 10th "element of hip hop".
[src:black-veganism/black-veganism] According to hip hop artist SupaNova Slom, young Black people turned to veganism in response to their older relatives' diet-caused health issues.
[src:black-veganism/black-veganism] Black vegans often face exotification of their food and culture by white vegan communities and spaces, which may alienate Black people from participating in the larger vegan community.
[src:black-veganism/black-veganism] A prime example of the appropriation and exotification of Black vegan cooking is in the popular vegan cooking blog, Thug Kitchen.
[src:black-veganism/black-veganism] This blog written in a style "borrowed heavily from African-American culture" and which had spawned book deals, was revealed as being authored by a white couple, Michelle Davis and Matt Holloway.
[src:black-veganism/black-veganism] Multiple critics described it as akin to blackface and pointed out the history of the use of the word "thug" as racially charged and typically used to describe Black men as criminals.
[src:black-veganism/black-veganism] Terry in 2014 described the blog and cookbooks as "whites masking in African-American street vernacular for their own amusement and profit", pointing out that the fact the couple had not identified themselves for two years was evidence of knowledge of the problematic nature of their behavior.
[src:black-veganism/black-veganism] After years of backlash about the name, in June 2020, in the midst of the George Floyd protests, the organization announced it would no longer be called Thug Kitchen.
[src:black-veganism/black-veganism] Hip Hop is Green is a US-based organization that uses hip hop events to promote veganism to Black youth as both a healthy choice and a political statement.
[src:black-veganism/black-veganism] The group held their first event in 2009 and in 2015 held one at the White House.
[src:black-veganism/black-veganism] Vegan Voices of Color argues that "mainstream veganism" is still "white veganism".
[src:black-veganism/black-veganism] The Food Empowerment Project is a vegan food justice advocacy group.
